### Pass by Reference

Pass by reference allows functions to modify the original variable without making a copy. It is also used to avoid copying large objects.

---

### Reference Syntax

```cpp
void func(int& ref) {
  ref = 100;  // Modifies original
}
```

---

### Modifying Arguments

```cpp
void increment(int& value) {
  value++;
}

int main() {
  int count = 5;
  increment(count);
  cout << count;  // 6
}
```

---

### Const Reference (Read-Only)

```cpp
void display(const vector<int>& data) {
  for (int x : data) {
    cout << x << " ";
  }
  // data.push_back(10);  // ERROR: const
}
```

---

### Multiple Return Values via Reference

```cpp
void divide(int dividend, int divisor, int& quotient, int& remainder) {
  quotient = dividend / divisor;
  remainder = dividend % divisor;
}

int q, r;
divide(17, 5, q, r);
// q = 3, r = 2
```

---

### Value vs Reference vs Const Reference

```cpp
void byValue(string s);          // Copy (slow for large strings)
void byRef(string& s);           // No copy, can modify
void byConstRef(const string& s); // No copy, read-only
```

---

> **Key Point:** Use pass by reference when you need to modify the argument or avoid copying large objects. Use pass by const reference for large objects you only need to read.

